<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="inv-5-7">
  <title>Investigation 5.7: Drive for Show, Putt for Dough</title>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises5-7" hidden-label="yes">
    <title>The Study</title>

    <p>This investigation compares how PGA scoring average relates to driving distance and putting average using <c>golfers18.txt</c>.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-a" label="I5.7.a"><title>Direction Conjecture: Driving</title><statement><p>(a) Predict direction of association between scoring average and driving distance.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-b" label="I5.7.b"><title>Direction Conjecture: Putting</title><statement><p>(b) Predict direction of association between scoring average and putting average.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-c" label="I5.7.c"><title>Compare Scatterplots</title><statement><p>(c) Produce both scatterplots and compare direction, form, and strength.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-d" label="I5.7.d"><title>Quadrant Reasoning</title><statement><p>(d) With mean lines shown, identify aligned vs non-aligned quadrants for both plots.</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Definition: Correlation Coefficient</title>
      <p>The correlation coefficient <m>r</m> measures strength and direction of a linear relationship and is unitless.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-e" label="I5.7.e"><title>Units of r</title><statement><p>(e) Use the formula to determine the units of <m>r</m> for putts vs strokes.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-f" label="I5.7.f"><title>Interpret r=0</title><statement><p>(f) If correlation equals zero, what might the scatterplot look like?</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-g" label="I5.7.g"><title>Correlation with Itself</title><statement><p>(g) What is the correlation of a variable with itself?</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-h" label="I5.7.h"><title>Resistance</title><statement><p>(h) Is correlation resistant to outliers? Explain.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-i" label="I5.7.i"><title>Rank Correlations from Plots</title><statement><p>(i) Rank provided scatterplots from strongest negative to strongest positive correlation.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-j" label="I5.7.j"><title>Compute Correlations with Technology</title><statement><p>(j) Compute and record correlation coefficients for each plot pair using applet/R/JMP.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-k" label="I5.7.k"><title>Range of r</title><statement><p>(k) State smallest and largest possible values of <m>r</m>.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-l" label="I5.7.l"><title>Sign of r</title><statement><p>(l) What sign of <m>r</m> corresponds to negative vs positive association?</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-m" label="I5.7.m"><title>Meaning of r near 0</title><statement><p>(m) What does <m>r</m> near zero signify?</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-n" label="I5.7.n"><title>Meaning of r near +-1</title><statement><p>(n) What does <m>r</m> close to 1 or -1 signify?</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-o" label="I5.7.o"><title>Cliche Check</title><statement><p>(o) Which variable has stronger correlation with scoring average: driving distance or putting average? Does this support the cliche?</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Study Conclusions</title>
      <p>The putting relationship with scoring average is typically stronger than the driving relationship in these data. Correlation quantifies linear association and should always be interpreted alongside scatterplots.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-practice-a" label="I5.7A"><title>Practice Problem 5.7A</title><statement><p>Reason about correlation when final exam scores are fixed transformations of midterm scores.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-7-practice-b" label="I5.7B"><title>Practice Problem 5.7B</title><statement><p>Match house-price scatterplots to correlation values and justify.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>
